50|$|<b>Ogoni</b> <b>people</b> live {{historically}} in the Niger Delta. Ogoniland oil {{facilities are}} operated mainly by the Shell Petroleum Development Corporation (Nigeria) in the upstream and the Nigerian National Petroleum Company in the downstream since the 1950s. The Ogoni campaign against Shell Oil {{is led by}} the Movement for the Survival of the <b>Ogoni</b> <b>People</b> (MOSOP). MOSOP is campaigning for the expulsion of Shell from Ogoniland.|$|E
50|$|One of {{the most}} {{prominent}} of these organisations to emerge in the region was the Movement for the Survival of the <b>Ogoni</b> <b>People</b> (MOSOP). The group declared that the <b>Ogoni</b> <b>people,</b> a small minority in Rivers state of Nigeria, were slowly being annihilated as the arable terrain of their homeland (known as Ogoniland) was degraded by pollution from oil production by Chevron and primarily Shell.|$|E
50|$|The Ogoni {{languages}}, or Kegboid languages, are {{the five}} languages of the <b>Ogoni</b> <b>people</b> of Rivers State, Nigeria.|$|E
